<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1324,359,1225]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Large polymorphic 
<taxonomicName box="[512,696,359,385]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phlaeothripinae">Phlaeothripinae</taxonomicName>
–Docessissophothripini. Antennae 
<number box="[1121,1133,359,385]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="8.0">8</number>
­segmented, III with 
<number box="[325,340,399,425]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1.0">1</number>
sense cone, IV with 
<number box="[592,607,399,425]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="3.0">3</number>
sense cones, VII and VIII broadly joined by oblique suture. Head about twice as long as wide, elevated in midline, narrowest just behind compound eyes (
<figureCitation box="[333,422,479,505]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[274,1315,285,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[271,1315,281,1290]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14. Majerthrips and Sennithrips species. (9) M. barrowi micropterous female, ventral; (10) M. barrowi micropterous female, dorsal; (11) M. barrowi apterous female, metanotum and tergites I – II; (12) S. psomus, ventral; (13) S. psomus, dorsal; (14) S. psomus antenna. [ns = prothoracic notopleural suture; ss = metathoracic sternopleural suture]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273406/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[389,422,479,505]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
); postocular setae capitate; postocellar setae acute in microptera, capitate in aptera; maxillary stylets retracted to compound eyes, close together in midline, maxillary guides stout; mouth cone pointed. Pronotum transverse, four pairs of capitate major setae present, anteromarginals absent (present in aptera); notopleural sutures complete. Mesonotal lateral setae capitate; metanotum reticulate, transverse in aptera; metanotal median setae acute (capitate in aptera). Prosternal basantra absent, ferna varying from pointed to rounded medially (
<figureCitation box="[616,690,719,745]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[274,1315,285,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[271,1315,281,1290]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14. Majerthrips and Sennithrips species. (9) M. barrowi micropterous female, ventral; (10) M. barrowi micropterous female, dorsal; (11) M. barrowi apterous female, metanotum and tergites I – II; (12) S. psomus, ventral; (13) S. psomus, dorsal; (14) S. psomus antenna. [ns = prothoracic notopleural suture; ss = metathoracic sternopleural suture]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273406/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[673,690,719,745]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
); mesopraesternum complete but eroded, particularly in aptera. Metathoracic sternopleural sutures long and curved (
<figureCitation box="[996,1067,759,785]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[274,1315,285,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[271,1315,281,1290]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14. Majerthrips and Sennithrips species. (9) M. barrowi micropterous female, ventral; (10) M. barrowi micropterous female, dorsal; (11) M. barrowi apterous female, metanotum and tergites I – II; (12) S. psomus, ventral; (13) S. psomus, dorsal; (14) S. psomus antenna. [ns = prothoracic notopleural suture; ss = metathoracic sternopleural suture]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273406/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1050,1067,759,785]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
), sometimes reaching almost hind coxal cavity. Both sexes with large fore femora and fore tarsal tooth. Forewings variable in length, also form of sub­basal setae, reaching thoracic hind margin in microptera, reaching tergite II hind margin in hemimacroptera. Pelta variable, quadrate to D­shaped (
<figureCitation box="[430,520,919,945]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[274,1315,285,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[271,1315,281,1290]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14. Majerthrips and Sennithrips species. (9) M. barrowi micropterous female, ventral; (10) M. barrowi micropterous female, dorsal; (11) M. barrowi apterous female, metanotum and tergites I – II; (12) S. psomus, ventral; (13) S. psomus, dorsal; (14) S. psomus antenna. [ns = prothoracic notopleural suture; ss = metathoracic sternopleural suture]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273406/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[488,520,919,945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
), but narrowly bell­shaped in aptera (
<figureCitation box="[982,1071,919,945]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[274,1315,285,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[271,1315,281,1290]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14. Majerthrips and Sennithrips species. (9) M. barrowi micropterous female, ventral; (10) M. barrowi micropterous female, dorsal; (11) M. barrowi apterous female, metanotum and tergites I – II; (12) S. psomus, ventral; (13) S. psomus, dorsal; (14) S. psomus antenna. [ns = prothoracic notopleural suture; ss = metathoracic sternopleural suture]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273406/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[1040,1071,919,945]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
); tergites II–VI each with 
<number box="[326,341,959,985]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2.0">2</number>
pairs of sigmoid wing­retaining setae, in microptera these are strongly developed only on III and IV, on VII they are short and straight as on all tergites of aptera; tergites with one pair of capitate posteromarginal setae, aptera with one pair of capitate setae medially (
<figureCitation box="[382,468,1079,1105]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 14" captionStartId="8.[264,382,1318,1342]" captionTargetBox="[274,1315,285,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[271,1315,281,1290]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 14. Majerthrips and Sennithrips species. (9) M. barrowi micropterous female, ventral; (10) M. barrowi micropterous female, dorsal; (11) M. barrowi apterous female, metanotum and tergites I – II; (12) S. psomus, ventral; (13) S. psomus, dorsal; (14) S. psomus antenna. [ns = prothoracic notopleural suture; ss = metathoracic sternopleural suture]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/273406/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[437,468,1079,1105]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
); tergite IX setae S 
<number box="[694,707,1079,1105]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1.0">1</number>
, S 
<number box="[735,750,1079,1105]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2.0">2</number>
and S 
<number box="[823,837,1079,1105]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="3.0">3</number>
capitate in both sexes. Sternites III–VI of both sexes anterolaterally with areas of specialised reticulation; sternal discal setae small in single transverse row.
</paragraph>
